<dl id="n12006k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12006k">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12006k"> 6(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> priest can quote Renan</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><mark>Alors, elle serait donc vraie cette parole de Renan</mark>: &ldquo; Le menhir qui se rencontre sur toute la surface de l&apos;ancien monde, depuis la Chine jusqu&apos;&agrave; l&apos;&icirc;le d&apos;Ouessant, n&apos;est rien autre chose qu&apos;un vivant t&eacute;moignage de sa foi au ciel.&rdquo; <br><font color="green">[Therefore Renan was right when he said &ldquo;The menhir, which one meets all over the ancient world, from China to the island of Ushant, is nothing other than a living witness of [mankind&apos;s]</font> faith in the heavens&rdquo;.] <small> l'Abb&eacute; A. Millon, <a name="AMPB" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#AMPB"><cite title="source">Pauvres Pierres! Les Megalithes Bretons devant la science</cite></a> (n.d) 24</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Joyce&apos;s note on the Abb&eacute; Millon&apos;s citation should be seen in the context of Renan&apos;s standing at this period. Not only his controversial <cite>La Vie de J&eacute;sus</cite>| (1863), but his complete works had been prohibited by the Catholic Church. </mm> </dd></dl>
